  "prompt": "Who were the leaders behind the Revolt of 1857?",
  "response": "The Revolt of 1857, also known as the Sepoy Mutiny or the First War of Independence, didn't have one singular leader. It was a widespread uprising with various figures leading in different regions and motivating the rebellion for different reasons. Here are some of the most prominent leaders:\n\n*   **Nana Sahib:** An adopted son of the last Peshwa Baji Rao II, he led the revolt in Kanpur. He felt unjustly deprived of his pension by the British.\n\n*   **Rani Lakshmibai:** The Queen of Jhansi, she was a symbol of resistance against British rule. She fought bravely after the British refused to recognize her adopted son as her heir.\n\n*   **Bahadur Shah Zafar:** The last Mughal Emperor, he was proclaimed the Emperor of India by the rebels in Delhi. Though reluctant, he became a figurehead for the rebellion, providing a sense of legitimacy.\n\n*   **Mangal Pandey:** A sepoy of the British East India Company, his act of defiance against the use of controversial rifle cartridges (rumored to be greased with animal fat) at Barrackpore ignited the initial spark of the revolt.\n\n*   **Tantia Tope:** A close associate of Nana Sahib, he was a brilliant general and guerrilla warfare expert. He played a crucial role in the revolt in Kanpur and the surrounding regions.\n\n*   **Kunwar Singh:** A zamindar (landowner) from Jagdishpur (Bihar), he led the revolt in Bihar. He was a veteran fighter who displayed great courage and strategic skill despite his advanced age.\n\n*   **Begum Hazrat Mahal:** The wife of the deposed Nawab of Awadh (Oudh), she led the revolt in Lucknow. She fought to reclaim her son's right to the throne.\n\n*   **Maulvi Ahmadullah Shah:** A religious leader from Faizabad, he was a powerful figure who rallied support for the revolt in Awadh.\n\nIt's important to note that the Revolt of 1857 was a complex event with diverse motivations and leadership. These are some of the most prominent figures, but many other local leaders and ordinary people also played important roles in the uprising.",
